WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.961 --> 00:00:08.666
<v ->Paul Perry has authored or coauthored 10 books</v>

2
00:00:08.666 --> 00:00:10.954
on the subject of near-death experiences.

3
00:00:10.954 --> 00:00:14.471
This 23 year long fascination began when he was approached

4
00:00:14.471 --> 00:00:16.410
to write a book titled The Light Beyond

5
00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:17.873
with Dr. Raymond Moody.

6
00:00:17.873 --> 00:00:20.880
Ten books later, Paul has used his knowledge of the subject

7
00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:23.643
and skills to produce a wonderful documentary

8
00:00:23.643 --> 00:00:25.141
titled Afterlife.

9
00:00:25.141 --> 00:00:27.579
The story follows a handful of people through their journey

10
00:00:27.579 --> 00:00:29.054
out of the body and back

11
00:00:29.054 --> 00:00:32.067
using science as a backdrop of understanding.

12
00:00:32.769 --> 00:00:34.619
<v Voiceover>Paul, it was wonderful watching your film</v>

13
00:00:34.619 --> 00:00:35.318
last night.

14
00:00:35.318 --> 00:00:36.126
<v ->Well thank you very much.</v>

15
00:00:36.126 --> 00:00:38.071
<v Voiceover>And you've done a beautiful job on Afterlife</v>

16
00:00:38.071 --> 00:00:41.934
and it's really a subject that I think is innately dear

17
00:00:41.934 --> 00:00:43.931
to every human being, whether we've had

18
00:00:43.931 --> 00:00:45.173
the experience or not.

19
00:00:45.173 --> 00:00:47.666
And there's been a lot of progress in the field

20
00:00:47.666 --> 00:00:50.611
and you've coauthored 10?

21
00:00:50.611 --> 00:00:53.444
<v ->Ten books on near-death experiences.</v>

22
00:00:53.444 --> 00:00:55.817
<v Voiceover>And you have one of them,</v>

23
00:00:55.817 --> 00:00:57.477
a New York Times best seller.

24
00:00:57.477 --> 00:00:59.784
<v ->There have been four New York Times best sellers actually.</v>

25
00:00:59.784 --> 00:01:01.221
<v Voiceover>And is this the recent one,</v>

26
00:01:01.221 --> 00:01:02.321
The Evidence of the Afterlife?

27
00:01:02.321 --> 00:01:05.019
<v ->That's correct. That was in February of 2010.</v>

28
00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:07.653
<v Voiceover>2010 and you cowrote it with Jeffrey Long</v>

29
00:01:07.653 --> 00:01:10.360
who is featured in the film, right?

30
00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:11.091
<v ->Right.</v>

31
00:01:11.091 --> 00:01:12.655
<v Voiceover>Along with Raymond Moody.</v>

32
00:01:12.655 --> 00:01:13.767
<v ->That's correct, yeah.</v>

33
00:01:13.767 --> 00:01:15.737
<v Voiceover>And we've talked with Dr. Moody</v>

34
00:01:15.737 --> 00:01:19.406
about the subject and his whole personal development

35
00:01:19.406 --> 00:01:20.834
of his work.

36
00:01:20.834 --> 00:01:23.829
And so now we want to look at some of the specifics

37
00:01:23.829 --> 00:01:25.176
that have happened that you have found

38
00:01:25.176 --> 00:01:26.973
through your research in terms of

39
00:01:26.973 --> 00:01:29.245
commonality of experience and so forth.

40
00:01:29.245 --> 00:01:30.940
And there are several things that

41
00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:32.611
struck me during this film.

42
00:01:32.611 --> 00:01:35.781
And so this is almost a continuation of our conversation

43
00:01:35.781 --> 00:01:38.753
in a sense with Dr. Moody because we're going on

44
00:01:38.753 --> 00:01:40.622
now into these areas.

45
00:01:40.622 --> 00:01:43.885
And one of the things that I think

46
00:01:43.885 --> 00:01:45.763
a lot of people have been curious about

47
00:01:45.763 --> 00:01:48.700
that you address in this is what happens

48
00:01:48.700 --> 00:01:51.573
to a person having a near-death experience

49
00:01:51.573 --> 00:01:55.310
based on their thinking,

50
00:01:55.310 --> 00:01:58.735
their religious beliefs or indoctrinations,

51
00:01:58.735 --> 00:02:00.903
societal indoctrinations and so forth.

52
00:02:00.903 --> 00:02:03.585
What have been the common themes that you've seen

53
00:02:03.585 --> 00:02:05.315
or are they not common?

54
00:02:05.315 --> 00:02:08.078
<v ->Well they are fairly common and that's the beauty</v>

55
00:02:08.078 --> 00:02:10.121
of near-death experiences is that

56
00:02:10.121 --> 00:02:14.347
the traits seem very common and the transformations

57
00:02:14.347 --> 00:02:16.623
afterwards are fairly common.

58
00:02:16.623 --> 00:02:19.684
And one of the transformations that happens to people

59
00:02:19.684 --> 00:02:21.298
who have near-death experiences is

60
00:02:21.298 --> 00:02:25.321
that they tend to become more type A

61
00:02:25.321 --> 00:02:26.598
type A without the anger.

62
00:02:26.598 --> 00:02:29.103
So they have a real zest for life

63
00:02:29.103 --> 00:02:31.436
and they have a zest for learning.

64
00:02:33.326 --> 00:02:36.510
Which in some ways surprises me and in some ways doesn't.

65
00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:38.518
You know, that they come out of this experience

66
00:02:38.518 --> 00:02:40.388
wanting to know more and more

67
00:02:40.388 --> 00:02:42.257
about the world they live in.

68
00:02:42.257 --> 00:02:46.645
The other thing is is that they become a lot more spiritual

69
00:02:48.125 --> 00:02:50.024
but they become less religious.

70
00:02:50.024 --> 00:02:50.991
And I always think...

71
00:02:50.991 --> 00:02:52.020
<v Voiceover>Big distinction.</v>

72
00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:53.219
<v ->It's a huge distinction.</v>

73
00:02:53.219 --> 00:02:55.100
The distinction to me is that

74
00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:56.865
it's almost like

75
00:03:00.625 --> 00:03:04.814
well, it's like being, how do I put this?

76
00:03:05.434 --> 00:03:07.194
It's the difference between working for the government

77
00:03:07.194 --> 00:03:08.573
and being an American.

78
00:03:08.573 --> 00:03:09.612
You know?

79
00:03:09.612 --> 00:03:12.253
And it's that way with people who have

80
00:03:12.253 --> 00:03:13.770
near-death experiences

81
00:03:13.770 --> 00:03:16.057
is that they become far more spiritual

82
00:03:16.057 --> 00:03:18.321
but they become less religious.

83
00:03:18.321 --> 00:03:21.154
So you find a lot of people who tend

84
00:03:21.154 --> 00:03:22.954
to drop out of churches

85
00:03:22.954 --> 00:03:25.589
and just become more spiritual.

86
00:03:25.589 --> 00:03:27.118
So near-death experiences really

87
00:03:27.118 --> 00:03:28.996
aren't great for church attendance,

88
00:03:28.996 --> 00:03:32.537
but they're kind of great for international consciousness.

89
00:03:32.537 --> 00:03:34.801
<v Voiceover>I can understand that because if you come back</v>

90
00:03:34.801 --> 00:03:38.771
with a sense of love, you know, as experienced

91
00:03:38.771 --> 00:03:41.012
on a different level than what you may have been

92
00:03:41.012 --> 00:03:43.648
able to access prior to the near-death experience,

93
00:03:43.648 --> 00:03:47.081
for most people that simply almost

94
00:03:47.081 --> 00:03:51.121
falls within the realm of whatever we call loosely spirit.

95
00:03:52.141 --> 00:03:55.385
So it makes sense, so it has to then be spiritual in nature

96
00:03:55.385 --> 00:03:56.894
for a person.

97
00:03:57.824 --> 00:04:01.060
And yet there are these overlays where you hear people

98
00:04:01.060 --> 00:04:03.471
that have these near-death experiences often say

99
00:04:03.471 --> 00:04:06.757
the image of Jesus came to them,

100
00:04:06.757 --> 00:04:10.542
or the image, if you're Islamic does

101
00:04:10.542 --> 00:04:12.543
the image of Muhammad come to people?

102
00:04:12.543 --> 00:04:13.244
<v ->Well...</v>

103
00:04:13.244 --> 00:04:14.875
<v Voiceover>Does Buddha come to people?</v>

104
00:04:14.875 --> 00:04:18.216
<v ->Yes, and I think Raymond would agree</v>

105
00:04:18.216 --> 00:04:21.281
as well as other researchers that when you talk to people

106
00:04:21.281 --> 00:04:24.319
about what they see in the light, you know,

107
00:04:24.319 --> 00:04:26.119
frequently you'll hear people say

108
00:04:26.119 --> 00:04:28.255
you know I saw Jesus

109
00:04:28.255 --> 00:04:30.391
if they're western orientation.

110
00:04:30.391 --> 00:04:33.433
Some children say I saw Santa Clause

111
00:04:33.433 --> 00:04:35.326
or I saw Grandpa.

112
00:04:35.326 --> 00:04:37.299
But then when you zero in a little bit more

113
00:04:37.299 --> 00:04:41.235
and you say, well, specifically what did they look like?

114
00:04:41.235 --> 00:04:43.267
Blah blah blah, they'll say, well,

115
00:04:43.267 --> 00:04:46.213
I didn't necessarily see features

116
00:04:46.213 --> 00:04:49.441
but I had the sense that it was Jesus

117
00:04:49.441 --> 00:04:51.275
or Santa Clause or Grandpa.

118
00:04:51.275 --> 00:04:53.481
And I think a lot of that relates to the fact

119
00:04:53.481 --> 00:04:55.823
that they feel that kind of comfort

120
00:04:55.823 --> 00:04:58.052
from the spirit that they're seeing in the light.

121
00:04:58.052 --> 00:05:00.418
<v Voiceover>That would make perfect sense.</v>

122
00:05:00.418 --> 00:05:03.692
And it's bringing in that trust and reverence

123
00:05:03.692 --> 00:05:05.456
that's already programmed within the being

124
00:05:05.456 --> 00:05:07.802
and applying an identity to it perhaps.

125
00:05:07.802 --> 00:05:09.069
<v ->Sure, I think that's true.</v>

126
00:05:09.069 --> 00:05:10.794
<v Voiceover>Which makes sense, it doesn't matter,</v>

127
00:05:10.794 --> 00:05:12.567
you're still having the experience.

128
00:05:12.567 --> 00:05:16.801
<v ->Yeah. Now I would love to spend more time with Muslims</v>

129
00:05:16.801 --> 00:05:18.679
who have had near-death experiences

130
00:05:18.679 --> 00:05:21.767
and see specifically what, find out specifically what

131
00:05:21.767 --> 00:05:23.474
it is they see in the light.

132
00:05:23.474 --> 00:05:25.239
<v Voiceover>I'm seeing a new book.</v>

133
00:05:25.239 --> 00:05:27.781
<v ->Well, actually we dealt with this to a large extent</v>

134
00:05:27.781 --> 00:05:29.476
in Evidence of the Afterlife

135
00:05:29.476 --> 00:05:32.054
where we had the luxury of having a lot of

136
00:05:32.054 --> 00:05:35.026
cross cultural near-death experiences.

137
00:05:35.026 --> 00:05:37.859
And we do find Muslims who see Muhammad

138
00:05:37.859 --> 00:05:40.924
which is, you know, not something you're supposed to do,

139
00:05:40.924 --> 00:05:42.503
you know he's not supposed to see

140
00:05:42.503 --> 00:05:45.335
representations of Muhammad.

141
00:05:45.335 --> 00:05:47.472
But they do anyway.

142
00:05:47.472 --> 00:05:49.770
<v Voiceover>Yeah and maybe an astronomer or astrophysicist</v>

143
00:05:49.770 --> 00:05:51.010
would see the cosmos.

144
00:05:51.010 --> 00:05:52.844
And many people see the cosmos anyway.

145
00:05:52.844 --> 00:05:55.178
<v ->They do see the cosmos, yeah sure.</v>

146
00:05:55.178 --> 00:05:56.675
<v Voiceover>Interesting.</v>

147
00:05:56.675 --> 00:06:00.248
And you, let's talk about children for a moment

148
00:06:00.248 --> 00:06:02.349
because a lot of times people say well this can

149
00:06:02.349 --> 00:06:05.507
certainly be an experience that has been conjured

150
00:06:06.527 --> 00:06:08.822
through, you know, our indoctrination

151
00:06:08.822 --> 00:06:11.260
or programming of some kind as we just talked about.

152
00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:12.758
Religious or otherwise.

153
00:06:12.758 --> 00:06:15.904
But can you give us a couple or a few cases

154
00:06:15.904 --> 00:06:18.737
of children and what they experience.

155
00:06:19.957 --> 00:06:22.274
Essentially to help us understand that

156
00:06:22.274 --> 00:06:24.979
this is bypassing analysis and programming

157
00:06:24.979 --> 00:06:27.905
to the same degree as an adult near-death experience.

158
00:06:27.905 --> 00:06:30.146
<v ->Right. Well the beauty of dealing with children</v>

159
00:06:30.146 --> 00:06:33.954
is that they haven't been, as we call it Oprahized yet.

160
00:06:33.954 --> 00:06:37.016
They haven't seen a lot of these things on television.

161
00:06:37.016 --> 00:06:39.651
They haven't read about them or necessarily

162
00:06:39.651 --> 00:06:41.254
talked about them with anyone else.

163
00:06:41.254 --> 00:06:42.716
They don't know anything about it.

164
00:06:42.716 --> 00:06:45.828
And suddenly a child will have a near death experience,

165
00:06:45.828 --> 00:06:48.963
they'll fall into a pool at the YMCA and drown

166
00:06:48.963 --> 00:06:51.331
or they'll have some kind of a disease.

167
00:06:51.331 --> 00:06:55.218
And they have an experience that is

168
00:06:55.218 --> 00:06:57.978
in many ways identical to an adult.

169
00:06:59.318 --> 00:07:02.184
The main difference with children is that they

170
00:07:02.184 --> 00:07:05.979
don't have much of a life review because they are children.

171
00:07:05.979 --> 00:07:09.021
And so that would be expected, but other than that

172
00:07:09.021 --> 00:07:13.955
the experiences are fairly identical with adults.

173
00:07:13.955 --> 00:07:17.293
I did a book with Melvin Morse years ago

174
00:07:17.293 --> 00:07:19.929
called Closer to the Light and it dealt with children

175
00:07:19.929 --> 00:07:21.659
and near-death experiences.

176
00:07:21.659 --> 00:07:25.200
And one of the things we found in our study

177
00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:28.636
of the children was that the light

178
00:07:28.636 --> 00:07:30.773
was hugely transformative.

179
00:07:30.773 --> 00:07:33.367
That children who

180
00:07:33.367 --> 00:07:35.678
somehow came into contact with the light

181
00:07:35.678 --> 00:07:39.044
were, as one child said, the light

182
00:07:39.044 --> 00:07:41.181
is where all the good things are.

183
00:07:41.181 --> 00:07:45.825
And we were able to do follow ups on some of these children

184
00:07:45.825 --> 00:07:48.492
and they've been transformed decades later

185
00:07:48.492 --> 00:07:50.384
by this experience.

186
00:07:50.384 --> 00:07:53.194
And we see the same thing with adults as well.

187
00:07:53.194 --> 00:07:56.003
The light is a very transformative element.

188
00:07:56.003 --> 00:08:00.006
And it's variously described as being

189
00:08:00.006 --> 00:08:02.873
just a brighter than bright light

190
00:08:02.873 --> 00:08:06.171
all the way to being a light that has substance

191
00:08:06.171 --> 00:08:09.677
that feels almost gelatinous that they go into it

192
00:08:09.677 --> 00:08:13.253
and they fell like they're walking through jello in a way.

193
00:08:13.253 --> 00:08:15.679
<v Voiceover>And some of this is almost, it seems that</v>

194
00:08:15.679 --> 00:08:19.290
filmmakers have captured some of what people describe

195
00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:21.461
to an extent, I mean it's fantasized a bit

196
00:08:21.461 --> 00:08:25.397
in films like What Dreams May Come, for example.

197
00:08:25.397 --> 00:08:29.202
Where you have this third dimensional looking landscape

198
00:08:29.202 --> 00:08:32.964
but with this gelatinous or otherworldly type of light

199
00:08:32.964 --> 00:08:35.541
and experience of colors beyond the spectrum

200
00:08:35.541 --> 00:08:37.445
we can perceive with our eyes,

201
00:08:37.445 --> 00:08:40.972
which would seem like it's kind of a close off

202
00:08:40.972 --> 00:08:43.213
dimensional field to where we are

203
00:08:43.213 --> 00:08:44.745
but not exactly.

204
00:08:44.745 --> 00:08:48.449
<v ->It is, and you know if you look at ancient history,</v>

205
00:08:48.449 --> 00:08:50.945
if you look at the Egyptians who dealt

206
00:08:50.945 --> 00:08:53.186
with the afterlife extensively in their art

207
00:08:53.186 --> 00:08:55.229
and in their other parts of their culture,

208
00:08:55.229 --> 00:08:59.490
they believed that the afterlife was right here.

209
00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:03.872
And that we would just step across into the afterlife.

210
00:09:03.872 --> 00:09:07.468
And so much of their art is representational of that.

211
00:09:07.468 --> 00:09:11.274
That literally you have people duck hunting

212
00:09:11.274 --> 00:09:13.975
in some of their art who are dead

213
00:09:13.975 --> 00:09:15.763
right next to you when you're duck hunting.

214
00:09:15.763 --> 00:09:17.284
You know, things like that.

215
00:09:17.284 --> 00:09:20.013
And that was their belief is that you just passed through

216
00:09:20.013 --> 00:09:21.917
kind of this little mirror.

217
00:09:21.917 --> 00:09:24.587
And it's, speaking of the Egyptians,

218
00:09:26.347 --> 00:09:27.652
well you know they are the first

219
00:09:27.652 --> 00:09:29.521
resurrection culture in history.

220
00:09:29.521 --> 00:09:33.933
And their whole culture was based on

221
00:09:33.933 --> 00:09:35.695
resurrection beliefs.

222
00:09:35.695 --> 00:09:40.025
And there are egyptologists who believe

223
00:09:40.025 --> 00:09:43.234
that the two sides

224
00:09:43.234 --> 00:09:45.080
of Egypt unified,

225
00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:48.005
north and south, they unified around

226
00:09:48.005 --> 00:09:50.710
things that were like death experiences.

227
00:09:50.710 --> 00:09:53.346
Now they describe these before Raymond Moody

228
00:09:53.346 --> 00:09:55.215
described near-death experiences.

229
00:09:55.215 --> 00:09:57.618
But what they've said in their writing was

230
00:09:57.618 --> 00:10:00.625
these people would sit around the campfire

231
00:10:00.625 --> 00:10:04.132
and they would talk about almost drowning in the Nile

232
00:10:04.132 --> 00:10:06.256
or being attacked by hippos when there actually

233
00:10:06.256 --> 00:10:10.099
were animals in the Nile, or crocodiles or having accidents.

234
00:10:10.099 --> 00:10:14.070
And going up tunnels, seeing bright lights,

235
00:10:14.070 --> 00:10:17.538
seeing dead relatives, having their heart

236
00:10:17.538 --> 00:10:21.741
weighed for it's goodness against the feather of truth.

237
00:10:21.741 --> 00:10:25.816
And if when you're in Egypt you see

238
00:10:25.816 --> 00:10:28.516
the representations of near-death experiences

239
00:10:28.516 --> 00:10:31.221
on the walls very vividly.

240
00:10:31.221 --> 00:10:34.959
And it says to me that, you know,

241
00:10:34.959 --> 00:10:36.724
the question what came first,

242
00:10:36.724 --> 00:10:38.764
the near-death experience or religion?

243
00:10:38.764 --> 00:10:41.133
To me the answer is near-death experience.

244
00:10:41.133 --> 00:10:44.035
And I think near-death experiences are really in many ways

245
00:10:44.035 --> 00:10:47.089
the wellspring for religion.

246
00:10:49.199 --> 00:10:53.239
It's religion's, religion is mankind's attempt

247
00:10:53.239 --> 00:10:56.351
to understand near-death experiences.

248
00:10:56.351 --> 00:10:58.481
It's mankind's attempt to understand

249
00:10:58.481 --> 00:11:00.280
what happens when we die.

250
00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:03.322
Then of course it grew into this enormous bureaucracy.

251
00:11:03.322 --> 00:11:06.991
But if you then look at how

252
00:11:06.991 --> 00:11:11.019
near-death experiences effect people now, it's like

253
00:11:11.019 --> 00:11:13.591
they go back and they eliminate all the bureaucracy

254
00:11:13.591 --> 00:11:15.228
and they go back to the pure form.

255
00:11:15.228 --> 00:11:17.561
<v Voiceover>And it's as though the Egyptians had the</v>

256
00:11:17.561 --> 00:11:19.965
cultural and spiritual framework

257
00:11:19.965 --> 00:11:23.773
to be able to comfortably articulate these experiences

258
00:11:23.773 --> 00:11:26.037
with each other and then preserve them

259
00:11:26.037 --> 00:11:28.463
in their hieroglyphics and such for future times

260
00:11:28.463 --> 00:11:30.414
to which right now we're coming back

